<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="17" pageNumber="17">Hab. India (Malabar); Ceylon; Sumatra; Celebes; Philippine Islands.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="17" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageId="17" pageNumber="17">This ant is plentiful in Malabar and the wooded parts of India; it forms a nest of living leaves which it draws together without detaching from the branch, and unites with a fine white web; sometimes the nest is a foot in diameter, but usually smaller. These societies are very numerous. (Jerdon, Madras Journ.)</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="17" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="17" pageNumber="17">
The short palpi and somewhat different neuration of the wings will probably render it necessary to remove this species from the genus 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:2506" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Formica" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Formica Linnaeus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Formica</taxonomicName>
, in which for the present we retain it.
</paragraph>
